---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";
---

<Layout
    title="Data Physicalization Workshop | tcplot: Data Visualization in Minneapolis and St. Paul"
    description="Hands-on workshop translating real datasets into physical objects you can hold."
>
    <div class="max-w-6xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8 py-8">
        <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto mt-8 mb-12">
            <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4">
                Upcoming: Data Physicalization Workshop — June 27th
            </h2>

            <div class="mb-6 text-gray-700">
                <p class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900">
                    Saturday, Jun 27 · 10:00 AM to 12:00 PM CDT
                </p>
                <p class="flex items-start gap-2 mt-1">
                    <svg
                        class="w-5 h-5 mt-0.5 shrink-0 text-gray-400"
                        viewBox="0 0 24 24"
                        fill="currentColor"
                        aria-hidden="true"
                    >
                        <path
                            fill-rule="evenodd"
                            d="M12 2c-3.866 0-7 3.07-7 6.857 0 4.34 4.686 9.86 6.412 11.74a.8.8 0 0 0 1.176 0C14.314 18.717 19 13.197 19 8.857 19 5.07 15.866 2 12 2Zm0 9.5a2.5 2.5 0 1 1 0-5 2.5 2.5 0 0 1 0 5Z"
                            clip-rule="evenodd"></path>
                    </svg>
                    <span
                        ><span class="font-semibold text-gray-900"
                            >The Coffee Shop NE</span
                        ><br />2852 Johnson St NE · Minneapolis, MN</span
                    >
                </p>
            </div>

            <div
                class="w-full max-w-[300px] mx-auto mb-4 rounded-lg overflow-hidden sm:float-left sm:mx-0 sm:mr-8 sm:w-[300px]"
            >
                <img
                    src="/images/legodata.gif"
                    alt="Animated clip of a data visualization built from colorful LEGO bricks"
                    class="w-full h-auto object-contain"
                />
            </div>

            <p class="text-xl text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
                What if your next chart wasn't on a screen?
            </p>
            <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
                Join <span class="font-silkscreen">tcplot</span> for a hands-on morning
                of data physicalization — translating real datasets into objects you
                can hold, turn over, and put on your desk. We'll explore paper, thread,
                beads, and the surprisingly hard question of what to encode when you
                can't reach for a library.
            </p>
            <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
                We'll draw inspiration from projects like Giorgia Lupi and
                Stefanie Posavec's <em>Dear Data</em>, Nathalie Miebach's
                weather sculptures, and the broader tradition of data
                physicalization (<a
                    href="https://dataphys.org"
                    target="_blank"
                    rel="noopener noreferrer"
                    class="text-blue-600 hover:underline">dataphys.org</a
                >). The constraint is the point: when you can't pipe data into
                ggplot, you have to make real decisions about hierarchy,
                encoding, and what's actually worth showing.
            </p>

            <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-3">
                What you'll do
            </h3>
            <ul class="space-y-3 text-gray-600 mb-8">
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="mt-1 text-gray-400">&#x25B8;</span>
                    <span
                        >Pick from a handful of small, pre-prepared datasets (<a
                            href="https://www.dnr.state.mn.us/climate/historical/daily.html"
                            target="_blank"
                            rel="noopener noreferrer"
                            class="text-blue-600 hover:underline"
                            >Twin Cities weather</a
                        >, <a
                            href="https://science.ebird.org/en/use-ebird-data/download-ebird-data-products"
                            target="_blank"
                            rel="noopener noreferrer"
                            class="text-blue-600 hover:underline"
                            >MN bird sightings</a
                        >, <a
                            href="https://opendata.minneapolismn.gov/"
                            target="_blank"
                            rel="noopener noreferrer"
                            class="text-blue-600 hover:underline"
                            >library checkouts</a
                        >, a week of your own personal data, or any other data)</span
                    >
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="mt-1 text-gray-400">&#x25B8;</span>
                    <span
                        >Work solo or in pairs to translate it into a physical
                        artifact</span
                    >
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="mt-1 text-gray-400">&#x25B8;</span>
                    <span>Share what you made and what surprised you</span>
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="mt-1 text-gray-400">&#x25B8;</span>
                    <span>Leave with the object you built</span>
                </li>
            </ul>

            <div class="clear-both"></div>

            <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-3">
                How the two hours will flow
            </h3>
            <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
                A loose schedule — we'll bend it to the room. The point is that
                you walk in with a dataset and walk out with an object.
            </p>
            <ul class="space-y-3 text-gray-600 mb-8">
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="mt-1 text-gray-400">&#x25B8;</span>
                    <span
                        ><span class="font-semibold text-gray-900"
                            >Welcome &amp; warm-up.</span
                        > Coffee, quick intros, and a gallery walk through real examples
                        — <em>Dear Data</em> postcards, Miebach's weather sculptures.</span
                    >
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="mt-1 text-gray-400">&#x25B8;</span>
                    <span
                        ><span class="font-semibold text-gray-900"
                            >Icebreaker.</span
                        > Everyone picks a project from <a
                            href="https://dataphys.org"
                            target="_blank"
                            rel="noopener noreferrer"
                            class="text-blue-600 hover:underline"
                            >dataphys.org</a
                        >, spends a few minutes with it, then explains it to the
                        group: what's the data, how is it encoded, and what
                        makes it work? A quick way to meet each other and warm
                        up the eye.</span
                    >
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="mt-1 text-gray-400">&#x25B8;</span>
                    <span
                        ><span class="font-semibold text-gray-900"
                            >Encoding without a library.</span
                        > A short crash course in the physical vocabulary of data.
                        On a screen you reach for <em>x</em>, <em>y</em>, color,
                        and size — in your hands you have far more to work with: <strong
                            >length</strong
                        > (a strand of thread, a torn strip of paper), <strong
                            >count</strong
                        > (how many beads on a string), <strong>position</strong
                        > and
                        <strong>order</strong> (near/far, stacked, sequenced),
                        <strong>color</strong> and <strong>texture</strong>
                        (smooth vs. rough, matte vs. shiny),
                        <strong>weight</strong>, <strong>height</strong>, and
                        even
                        <strong>negative space</strong> (the gaps that say as much
                        as the marks). We'll talk about which channels the hand and
                        eye read most easily, when an encoding is honest versus merely
                        pretty, and the trade-off at the center of all of this: you
                        can only encode a few variables before an object stops being
                        legible, so choosing what to
                        <em>leave out</em> is the real craft. Then I'll turn a single
                        row of data into an object live — narrating each choice —
                        so you can see the decisions in real time before you make
                        your own.</span
                    >
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="mt-1 text-gray-400">&#x25B8;</span>
                    <span
                        ><span class="font-semibold text-gray-900"
                            >Pick &amp; sketch.</span
                        > Choose your dataset, name the one question you want it to
                        answer, and rough out your encoding on paper
                        <em>before</em> you touch the beads.</span
                    >
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="mt-1 text-gray-400">&#x25B8;</span>
                    <span
                        ><span class="font-semibold text-gray-900">Make.</span> The
                        heart of it — build your artifact, solo or in pairs. I'll
                        circulate with prompts when you get stuck and more supplies
                        when you get ambitious.</span
                    >
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="mt-1 text-gray-400">&#x25B8;</span>
                    <span
                        ><span class="font-semibold text-gray-900"
                            >Show &amp; tell.</span
                        > Pass your object around the table. Tell us what you encoded,
                        what you had to leave out, and what surprised you when the
                        data became something you could hold.</span
                    >
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="mt-1 text-gray-400">&#x25B8;</span>
                    <span
                        ><span class="font-semibold text-gray-900">Wrap.</span> A
                        group photo of everything we made, a few pointers for going
                        further, and you take your object home.</span
                    >
                </li>
            </ul>

            <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-3">
                Datasets to choose from
            </h3>
            <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
                These are real, ready to use, and small enough to build in two
                hours. They range in complexity — start simple or take on
                something with more to juggle.
            </p>

            <h4 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-2">
                Twin Cities weather — this week
            </h4>
            <p class="text-base text-gray-500 leading-relaxed mb-3">
                The actual forecast for Minneapolis, the week starting Sunday.
                Five days, several variables — a good medium-complexity pick.
            </p>
            <div class="overflow-x-auto mb-2">
                <table class="w-full text-left text-gray-600 border-collapse">
                    <thead>
                        <tr
                            class="border-b border-gray-300 text-sm uppercase tracking-wide text-gray-500"
                        >
                            <th class="py-2 pr-4 font-semibold">Day</th>
                            <th class="py-2 pr-4 font-semibold">High °F</th>
                            <th class="py-2 pr-4 font-semibold">Low °F</th>
                            <th class="py-2 pr-4 font-semibold">Rain chance</th>
                            <th class="py-2 font-semibold">Conditions</th>
                        </tr>
                    </thead>
                    <tbody>
                        <tr class="border-b border-gray-100">
                            <td class="py-2 pr-4">Sun, Jun 28</td>
                            <td class="py-2 pr-4">89</td>
                            <td class="py-2 pr-4">76</td>
                            <td class="py-2 pr-4">57%</td>
                            <td class="py-2"
                                >Showers &amp; thunderstorms likely</td
                            >
                        </tr>
                        <tr class="border-b border-gray-100">
                            <td class="py-2 pr-4">Mon, Jun 29</td>
                            <td class="py-2 pr-4">97</td>
                            <td class="py-2 pr-4">76</td>
                            <td class="py-2 pr-4">12%</td>
                            <td class="py-2">Sunny</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr class="border-b border-gray-100">
                            <td class="py-2 pr-4">Tue, Jun 30</td>
                            <td class="py-2 pr-4">95</td>
                            <td class="py-2 pr-4">72</td>
                            <td class="py-2 pr-4">40%</td>
                            <td class="py-2">Chance of storms</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr class="border-b border-gray-100">
                            <td class="py-2 pr-4">Wed, Jul 1</td>
                            <td class="py-2 pr-4">94</td>
                            <td class="py-2 pr-4">73</td>
                            <td class="py-2 pr-4">33%</td>
                            <td class="py-2">Chance of storms</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr class="border-b border-gray-100">
                            <td class="py-2 pr-4">Thu, Jul 2</td>
                            <td class="py-2 pr-4">94</td>
                            <td class="py-2 pr-4">73</td>
                            <td class="py-2 pr-4">47%</td>
                            <td class="py-2">Chance of storms</td>
                        </tr>
                    </tbody>
                </table>
            </div>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-400 mb-8">
                National Weather Service. (2026). <em
                    >Point forecast for Minneapolis, MN (44.98°N, 93.27°W)</em
                > [Data set]. National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration. Retrieved
                June 26, 2026, from <a
                    href="https://api.weather.gov/gridpoints/MPX/108,72/forecast"
                    target="_blank"
                    rel="noopener noreferrer"
                    class="text-blue-600 hover:underline"
                    >https://api.weather.gov/gridpoints/MPX/108,72/forecast</a
                >. The published forecast reaches Thursday; the weekend isn't
                out yet.
            </p>

            <h4 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-2">
                Minnesota bird sightings — spring
            </h4>
            <p class="text-base text-gray-500 leading-relaxed mb-3">
                The most-reported birds across Minnesota this May and June. One
                category, one number — the simplest place to start.
            </p>
            <div class="overflow-x-auto mb-2">
                <table class="w-full text-left text-gray-600 border-collapse">
                    <thead>
                        <tr
                            class="border-b border-gray-300 text-sm uppercase tracking-wide text-gray-500"
                        >
                            <th class="py-2 pr-4 font-semibold">Species</th>
                            <th class="py-2 font-semibold">Observations</th>
                        </tr>
                    </thead>
                    <tbody>
                        <tr class="border-b border-gray-100">
                            <td class="py-2 pr-4">Red-winged Blackbird</td>
                            <td class="py-2">319</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr class="border-b border-gray-100">
                            <td class="py-2 pr-4">Mallard</td>
                            <td class="py-2">284</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr class="border-b border-gray-100">
                            <td class="py-2 pr-4">American Robin</td>
                            <td class="py-2">283</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr class="border-b border-gray-100">
                            <td class="py-2 pr-4">Canada Goose</td>
                            <td class="py-2">235</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr class="border-b border-gray-100">
                            <td class="py-2 pr-4">Baltimore Oriole</td>
                            <td class="py-2">194</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr class="border-b border-gray-100">
                            <td class="py-2 pr-4">Yellow-rumped Warbler</td>
                            <td class="py-2">192</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr class="border-b border-gray-100">
                            <td class="py-2 pr-4">Rose-breasted Grosbeak</td>
                            <td class="py-2">177</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr class="border-b border-gray-100">
                            <td class="py-2 pr-4">Wild Turkey</td>
                            <td class="py-2">153</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr class="border-b border-gray-100">
                            <td class="py-2 pr-4">Song Sparrow</td>
                            <td class="py-2">142</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr class="border-b border-gray-100">
                            <td class="py-2 pr-4">American Goldfinch</td>
                            <td class="py-2">132</td>
                        </tr>
                    </tbody>
                </table>
            </div>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-400 mb-8">
                GBIF.org. (2026). <em
                    >Occurrence search: Aves (birds), Minnesota, United States,
                    May–June 2026</em
                > [Data set]. Global Biodiversity Information Facility. Retrieved
                June 26, 2026, from <a
                    href="https://www.gbif.org/occurrence/search?country=US&state_province=Minnesota&taxon_key=212&year=2026"
                    target="_blank"
                    rel="noopener noreferrer"
                    class="text-blue-600 hover:underline"
                    >https://www.gbif.org/occurrence/search</a
                >. Counts are the number of recorded observations.
            </p>

            <h4 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-2">
                The planets — by the numbers
            </h4>
            <p class="text-base text-gray-500 leading-relaxed mb-3">
                The eight planets (plus Pluto), with four properties chosen
                because they map so naturally onto things you can make: size,
                weight, force, and position. A natural fit for a hanging mobile
                or a beaded model of the solar system.
            </p>
            <div class="overflow-x-auto mb-2">
                <table class="w-full text-left text-gray-600 border-collapse">
                    <thead>
                        <tr
                            class="border-b border-gray-300 text-sm uppercase tracking-wide text-gray-500"
                        >
                            <th class="py-2 pr-4 font-semibold">Planet</th>
                            <th class="py-2 pr-4 font-semibold">Diameter (km)</th>
                            <th class="py-2 pr-4 font-semibold">Mass (10²⁴ kg)</th>
                            <th class="py-2 pr-4 font-semibold">Gravity (m/s²)</th>
                            <th class="py-2 font-semibold">Dist. from Sun (10⁶ km)</th>
                        </tr>
                    </thead>
                    <tbody>
                        <tr class="border-b border-gray-100">
                            <td class="py-2 pr-4">Mercury</td>
                            <td class="py-2 pr-4">4879</td>
                            <td class="py-2 pr-4">0.330</td>
                            <td class="py-2 pr-4">3.7</td>
                            <td class="py-2">57.9</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr class="border-b border-gray-100">
                            <td class="py-2 pr-4">Venus</td>
                            <td class="py-2 pr-4">12104</td>
                            <td class="py-2 pr-4">4.87</td>
                            <td class="py-2 pr-4">8.9</td>
                            <td class="py-2">108.2</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr class="border-b border-gray-100">
                            <td class="py-2 pr-4">Earth</td>
                            <td class="py-2 pr-4">12756</td>
                            <td class="py-2 pr-4">5.97</td>
                            <td class="py-2 pr-4">9.8</td>
                            <td class="py-2">149.6</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr class="border-b border-gray-100">
                            <td class="py-2 pr-4">Mars</td>
                            <td class="py-2 pr-4">6792</td>
                            <td class="py-2 pr-4">0.642</td>
                            <td class="py-2 pr-4">3.7</td>
                            <td class="py-2">227.9</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr class="border-b border-gray-100">
                            <td class="py-2 pr-4">Jupiter</td>
                            <td class="py-2 pr-4">142984</td>
                            <td class="py-2 pr-4">1898</td>
                            <td class="py-2 pr-4">23.1</td>
                            <td class="py-2">778.6</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr class="border-b border-gray-100">
                            <td class="py-2 pr-4">Saturn</td>
                            <td class="py-2 pr-4">120536</td>
                            <td class="py-2 pr-4">568</td>
                            <td class="py-2 pr-4">9.0</td>
                            <td class="py-2">1433.5</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr class="border-b border-gray-100">
                            <td class="py-2 pr-4">Uranus</td>
                            <td class="py-2 pr-4">51118</td>
                            <td class="py-2 pr-4">86.8</td>
                            <td class="py-2 pr-4">8.7</td>
                            <td class="py-2">2872.5</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr class="border-b border-gray-100">
                            <td class="py-2 pr-4">Neptune</td>
                            <td class="py-2 pr-4">49528</td>
                            <td class="py-2 pr-4">102</td>
                            <td class="py-2 pr-4">11.0</td>
                            <td class="py-2">4495.1</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr class="border-b border-gray-100">
                            <td class="py-2 pr-4">Pluto</td>
                            <td class="py-2 pr-4">2370</td>
                            <td class="py-2 pr-4">0.0146</td>
                            <td class="py-2 pr-4">0.7</td>
                            <td class="py-2">5906.4</td>
                        </tr>
                    </tbody>
                </table>
            </div>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-400 mb-8">
                Williams, D. R. (2024). <em>Planetary fact sheet</em> [Data set].
                NASA Goddard Space Flight Center, National Space Science Data
                Center. Retrieved June 26, 2026, from <a
                    href="https://nssdc.gsfc.nasa.gov/planetary/factsheet/"
                    target="_blank"
                    rel="noopener noreferrer"
                    class="text-blue-600 hover:underline"
                    >https://nssdc.gsfc.nasa.gov/planetary/factsheet/</a
                >. Negative rotation periods indicate retrograde spin.
            </p>

            <h4 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-2">
                Your own steps — from your phone
            </h4>
            <p class="text-base text-gray-500 leading-relaxed mb-8">
                Open the health app on your phone (Apple Health, Google Fit,
                Fitbit, whatever you carry) and read off the miles you walked
                each day this past week. Seven numbers, completely your own —
                ideal for a bracelet or a small loom.
            </p>

            <h4 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-2">
                Library checkouts — bring your own
            </h4>
            <p class="text-base text-gray-500 leading-relaxed mb-8">
                For a more complex challenge, pull a live slice of Twin Cities
                library data from <a
                    href="https://opendata.minneapolismn.gov/"
                    target="_blank"
                    rel="noopener noreferrer"
                    class="text-blue-600 hover:underline"
                    >Minneapolis Open Data</a
                > — checkouts by branch, item, or month carry several variables at
                once, so you'll have to decide what to keep and what to drop.
            </p>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-400 mb-8">
                City of Minneapolis. (n.d.). <em>Minneapolis Open Data</em> [Data
                portal]. Retrieved June 26, 2026, from <a
                    href="https://opendata.minneapolismn.gov/"
                    target="_blank"
                    rel="noopener noreferrer"
                    class="text-blue-600 hover:underline"
                    >https://opendata.minneapolismn.gov/</a
                >.
            </p>

            <h4 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-2">
                More fun datasets to download
            </h4>
            <p class="text-base text-gray-500 leading-relaxed mb-3">
                Want something different? These are free CSVs, small enough to
                encode by hand. The big ones — just grab a handful of rows or a
                single season.
            </p>
            <ul class="space-y-3 text-gray-600 mb-8">
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="mt-1 text-gray-400">&#x25B8;</span>
                    <span
                        ><a
                            href="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/rfordatascience/tidytuesday/master/data/2023/2023-02-21/bob_ross.csv"
                            target="_blank"
                            rel="noopener noreferrer"
                            class="text-blue-600 hover:underline"
                            >Bob Ross paintings</a
                        > — the exact paint colors used in every episode of
                        <em>The Joy of Painting</em>. A bead per color is almost
                        too perfect; pick one season.</span
                    >
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="mt-1 text-gray-400">&#x25B8;</span>
                    <span
                        ><a
                            href="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/allisonhorst/palmerpenguins/main/inst/extdata/penguins.csv"
                            target="_blank"
                            rel="noopener noreferrer"
                            class="text-blue-600 hover:underline"
                            >Palmer Penguins</a
                        > — bill, flipper, and body size for three Antarctic penguin
                        species. Map a strip of paper to each flipper length; grab
                        a handful of rows.</span
                    >
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="mt-1 text-gray-400">&#x25B8;</span>
                    <span
                        ><a
                            href="https://vincentarelbundock.github.io/Rdatasets/csv/datasets/mtcars.csv"
                            target="_blank"
                            rel="noopener noreferrer"
                            class="text-blue-600 hover:underline">mtcars</a
                        > — 32 classic cars by horsepower, weight, and fuel economy.
                        A tidy, all-numeric set that bars and beads love.</span
                    >
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="mt-1 text-gray-400">&#x25B8;</span>
                    <span
                        ><a
                            href="https://vincentarelbundock.github.io/Rdatasets/csv/datasets/HairEyeColor.csv"
                            target="_blank"
                            rel="noopener noreferrer"
                            class="text-blue-600 hover:underline"
                            >Hair &amp; eye color</a
                        > — counts of people by hair and eye color. A natural fit
                        when the encoding is literally the color.</span
                    >
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="mt-1 text-gray-400">&#x25B8;</span>
                    <span
                        ><a
                            href="https://vincentarelbundock.github.io/Rdatasets/csv/datasets/anscombe.csv"
                            target="_blank"
                            rel="noopener noreferrer"
                            class="text-blue-600 hover:underline"
                            >Anscombe's quartet</a
                        > — four tiny datasets with identical statistics but wildly
                        different shapes. Build all four and feel the difference.</span
                    >
                </li>
            </ul>

            <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-3">
                What we'll provide
            </h3>
            <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
                Cardstock, embroidery thread, beads, tape, markers, making
                supplies, datasets ready to go.
            </p>

            <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-3">
                Ideas to get you started
            </h3>
            <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
                Not sure where to begin? Here are a few forms that translate
                data especially well — but treat them as springboards, not
                instructions.
            </p>
            <ul class="space-y-3 text-gray-600 mb-6">
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="mt-1 text-gray-400">&#x25B8;</span>
                    <span
                        ><span class="font-semibold text-gray-900"
                            >Wire-and-bead jewelry.</span
                        > Thread a bracelet or necklace where each bead is a day,
                        a row, or an event — color for category, size for magnitude,
                        spacing for the gaps in between. You leave wearing your data.</span
                    >
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="mt-1 text-gray-400">&#x25B8;</span>
                    <span
                        ><span class="font-semibold text-gray-900"
                            >Altoid-tin looms.</span
                        > Notch the lip of a tin, string a warp across it, and weave:
                        let the colors of the weft rows encode one variable and the
                        bands of the warp another. A whole woven dataset that snaps
                        shut in your pocket.</span
                    >
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="mt-1 text-gray-400">&#x25B8;</span>
                    <span
                        ><span class="font-semibold text-gray-900"
                            >Layered paper topography.</span
                        > Cut and stack cardstock contours so a value over time rises
                        into a little 3D landscape — peaks for the highs, valleys
                        for the lows, something you read with your fingertips.</span
                    >
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="mt-1 text-gray-400">&#x25B8;</span>
                    <span
                        ><span class="font-semibold text-gray-900"
                            >Hanging mobiles.</span
                        > Suspend tagged elements from thread and let the piece find
                        its own balance — arm length and height encode the numbers
                        while gravity does the comparing for you.</span
                    >
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="mt-1 text-gray-400">&#x25B8;</span>
                    <span
                        ><span class="font-semibold text-gray-900"
                            >Punch-card strips.</span
                        > Punch holes into a ribbon of cardstock, player-piano style
                        — present or absent, more or fewer — so a week of yes/no data
                        becomes a strip you can run through your hands.</span
                    >
                </li>
            </ul>

            <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-3">
                What to bring
            </h3>
            <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
                Yourself. Optionally, a week of personal data you've been
                tracking (sleep, coffee, steps, moods, anything) or your own
                craft supplies of choice.
            </p>

            <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-3">
                Who this is for
            </h3>
            <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
                Anyone curious about data visualization — practitioners working
                in D3, Tableau, ggplot2, Observable, or none of the above. No
                craft skills required.
            </p>

            <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 leading-relaxed">
                Hope to see you there!
            </p>

            <div class="flex justify-center mt-12">
                <div class="max-w-2xl w-full">
                    <div class="rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
                        <img
                            src="/images/hailmary.jpeg"
                            alt="Physical star model made of wire and beads radiating from a central point, from the movie Project Hail Mary"
                            class="w-full h-auto object-contain"
                        />
                    </div>
                    <p class="text-sm text-gray-400 mt-2 text-center italic">
                        Still from <em>Project Hail Mary</em>. Dir. Phil Lord
                        and Christopher Miller. Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer, 2026.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mt-16 mb-3">
                Books on the table
            </h3>
            <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
                A small library will be out for you to flip through whenever you
                need a spark, a reference, or a reason to step back from the
                glue.
            </p>
            <ul class="space-y-5 text-gray-600 mb-6">
                <li>
                    <span class="font-semibold text-gray-900"
                        >Observe, Collect, Draw!</span
                    > — Giorgia Lupi &amp; Stefanie Posavec. A guided journal that
                    turns the <em>Dear Data</em> method into a workbook: track your
                    own life and hand-draw it.
                    <span class="block text-gray-500 mt-1"
                        >Why it's here: the fastest on-ramp to encoding personal
                        data by hand — exactly what you'll be doing today.</span
                    >
                </li>
                <li>
                    <span class="font-semibold text-gray-900">Dear Data</span> — Giorgia
                    Lupi &amp; Stefanie Posavec. A year of weekly postcards in which
                    two designers mailed each other hand-drawn visualizations of their
                    everyday lives.
                    <span class="block text-gray-500 mt-1"
                        >Why it's here: the founding text for slow, analog,
                        deeply personal data — proof that a chart can be made
                        entirely by hand and be the better for it.</span
                    >
                </li>
                <li>
                    <span class="font-semibold text-gray-900">Speak Data</span> —
                    Giorgia Lupi &amp; Phillip Cox. Conversations with artists, scientists,
                    thinkers, and dreamers about how we live our lives in numbers,
                    grounded in Lupi's idea of Data Humanism.
                    <span class="block text-gray-500 mt-1"
                        >Why it's here: it reframes data as something human and
                        felt rather than purely technical — the mindset behind
                        making data you can hold.</span
                    >
                </li>
                <li>
                    <span class="font-semibold text-gray-900"
                        >Code as Creative Medium</span
                    > — Golan Levin &amp; Tega Brain. A handbook of exercises and
                    assignments for teaching and learning creative coding and generative
                    art.
                    <span class="block text-gray-500 mt-1"
                        >Why it's here: a deep well of generative,
                        constraint-led prompts — many translate straight from
                        screen to scissors and thread.</span
                    >
                </li>
                <li>
                    <span class="font-semibold text-gray-900"
                        >Beautiful Evidence</span
                    > — Edward Tufte. On how evidence becomes argument: sparklines,
                    mapped pictures, and the integrity of showing data honestly.
                    <span class="block text-gray-500 mt-1"
                        >Why it's here: the discipline of encoding truthfully —
                        a useful conscience when you're tempted to choose pretty
                        over honest.</span
                    >
                </li>
                <li>
                    <span class="font-semibold text-gray-900"
                        >Envisioning Information</span
                    > — Edward Tufte. A classic on escaping flatland: layering, small
                    multiples, and packing many dimensions into a clear image.
                    <span class="block text-gray-500 mt-1"
                        >Why it's here: physical objects are inherently
                        multi-dimensional, and this is the master class in
                        managing that density without losing the reader.</span
                    >
                </li>
                <li>
                    <span class="font-semibold text-gray-900"
                        >The Book of Circles</span
                    > — Manuel Lima. A visual history of circular information design,
                    from ancient diagrams to modern network graphics.
                    <span class="block text-gray-500 mt-1"
                        >Why it's here: a catalog of non-rectangular layouts to
                        steal from when a grid feels too obvious for your
                        object.</span
                    >
                </li>
                <li>
                    <span class="font-semibold text-gray-900"
                        >Nightingale, Issues 1–3</span
                    > — the Data Visualization Society. The society's print journal,
                    full of essays, interviews, and showcase work from across the
                    dataviz field.
                    <span class="block text-gray-500 mt-1"
                        >Why it's here: a snapshot of where the field is right
                        now — community, debates, and plenty of fresh visual
                        inspiration.</span
                    >
                </li>
                <li>
                    <span class="font-semibold text-gray-900"
                        >Value and Transformation of Corals</span
                    > — Christine &amp; Margaret Wertheim. The catalog of the Crochet
                    Coral Reef, a global craftivist project translating marine ecology
                    — and hyperbolic geometry — into crocheted yarn.
                    <span class="block text-gray-500 mt-1"
                        >Why it's here: the most ambitious example of data and
                        science made physical by hand, at the scale of a
                        movement — proof of how far this practice can go.</span
                    >
                </li>
            </ul>
        </div>
    </div>
</Layout>
